<worksheet xml:id="activity-tutorial-4">
  <title>Tutorial-4</title>
  <introduction>
                <p>
                    Following exercises are taken from Sections 13.3 and 13.4 of the book <em>Abstract Algebra</em> by Dummit and Foote.
                </p>
  </introduction>
  <page>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Show that it is impossible to construct a regular <m>9</m>-gon with straightedge and compass.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the fact that <m>\alpha=2\cos(2\pi/5)</m> satisfies the equation <m>x^2+x-1=0</m> to construct a regular pentagon with straightedge and compass.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Determine the splittting field and degree over <m>\Q</m> of the following polynomials.
                <me>
                    x^4-2;\quad x^4+2;\quad x^4+x^2+1;\quad\text{and}\quad x^6-4
                </me>    
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>K/F</m> be a finite field extension. Show that <m>K</m> is a splitting field over <m>F</m> if and only if every irreducible polynomial in <m>F[x]</m> that has a root in <m>K</m> splits completely in <m>K[x]</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>K_1,K_2</m> be finite extensions of a field <m>F</m> contained in a field <m>K</m>. Furthermore, assume that <m>K_1,K_2</m> are splitting fields over <m>F</m>. Show that <m>K_1K_2</m> and <m>K_1\cap K_2</m> are splitting fields over <m>F</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>
